    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"code\",\n",
    "   \"execution_count\": null,\n",
    "   \"id\": \"c014\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"outputs\": [],\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"# Scatter: logins vs satisfaction colored by outcome\\n\",\n",
    "    \"fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))\\n\",\n",
    "    \"colors = {\\\"Renewed\\\": \\\"#2ecc71\\\", \\\"Cancelled\\\": \\\"#e74c3c\\\", \\\"Downgraded\\\": \\\"#f39c12\\\"}\\n\",\n",
    "    \"for outcome in [\\\"Renewed\\\", \\\"Downgraded\\\", \\\"Cancelled\\\"]:\\n\",\n",
    "    \"    subset = df[df[\\\"outcome\\\"] == outcome].sample(min(300, len(df[df[\\\"outcome\\\"]==outcome])), random_state=SEED)\\n\",\n",
    "    \"    ax.scatter(subset[\\\"logins_last_30d\\\"], subset[\\\"satisfaction_score\\\"],\\n\",\n",
    "    \"              alpha=0.4, label=outcome, color=colors[outcome], s=20)\\n\",\n",
    "    \"ax.set_xlabel(\\\"Logins (Last 30 Days)\\\")\\n\",\n",
    "    \"ax.set_ylabel(\\\"Satisfaction Score\\\")\\n\",\n",
    "    \"ax.set_title(\\\"Logins vs Satisfaction by Outcome\\\")\\n\",\n",
    "    \"ax.legend()\\n\",\n",
    "    \"plt.tight_layout()\\n\",\n",
    "    \"plt.show()\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"markdown\",\n",
    "   \"id\": \"m016\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"## Key Findings\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"1. **Satisfaction score is the strongest single predictor of renewal.** Subscribers scoring ≥7 renew at much higher rates.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"2. **Login frequency strongly differentiates churners from renewers.** Low-usage subscribers are at highest risk.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"3. **Premium plan holders renew more often,** likely because they're more invested and use more features.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"4. **Support tickets are a weak but meaningful negative signal.** Frequent support contact may indicate friction.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"5. **Tenure has a modest positive effect** — longer-tenured subscribers have established habits and are more likely to stay.\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"markdown\",\n",
    "   \"id\": \"m017\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"## Limitations\\n\",\n",
    "    \"- Synthetic data with engineered outcome dependencies.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"- No price sensitivity or competitive switching data.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"- No temporal pattern (seasonal renewal effects).\\n\",\n",
    "    \"- Satisfaction is a single point-in-time score, not a trend.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"- No distinction between voluntary and involuntary churn (payment failure).\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"markdown\",\n",
    "   \"id\": \"m018\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"## Recommendations / Next Steps\\n\",\n",
    "    \"1. **Flag subscribers with low logins + low satisfaction** for proactive outreach.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"2. **Invest in onboarding for Basic plan users** to increase feature adoption.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"3. **Conduct post-cancellation surveys** to identify fixable issues.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"4. **Build a predictive churn model** using the signals identified here.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"5. **Track satisfaction trends,** not just snapshots — declining scores are stronger signals than absolute values.\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"markdown\",\n",
    "   \"id\": \"m019\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"## Common Mistakes\\n\",\n",
    "    \"1. **Treating all churn the same.** Voluntary cancellation, involuntary (payment failure), and downgrades have different causes.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"2. **Using overall churn rate without segmentation.** Plan, tenure, and usage segments have very different risk profiles.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"3. **Intervening too late.** By the time a subscriber contacts support to cancel, the decision is usually made.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"4. **Ignoring \\\"silent\\\" churners.** Subscribers who stop using the product but haven't cancelled yet are high-risk.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"5. **Assuming correlation implies causation.** High satisfaction correlates with renewal, but mandating surveys won't reduce churn.\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"markdown\",\n",
    "   \"id\": \"m020\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"## Mini Challenge / Exercises\\n\",\n",
    "    \"1. **Create a risk score** (0-100) combining logins, satisfaction, and features used. Segment subscribers into Low/Medium/High risk.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"2. **Build a simple decision tree** to predict outcome from the available features. Which splits matter most?\\n\",\n",
    "    \"3. **Compute monthly churn rate** by cohort if you add a signup_month column.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"4. **Estimate the revenue at risk** from subscribers classified as High risk.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"5. **Design an intervention experiment:** What would you test to improve renewal rates for the riskiest segment?\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"markdown\",\n",
    "   \"id\": \"m021\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"## Final Summary / Key Takeaways\\n\",\n",
    "    \"- **Engagement and satisfaction are the strongest renewal predictors.** Monitor both proactively.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"- **Premium subscribers churn less,** but this may reflect selection bias rather than plan design.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"- **Low-engagement subscribers are the primary risk group.** Intervene before they go silent.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"- **Combine quantitative analysis with qualitative exit interviews** for a complete picture.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"- **This EDA provides a strong foundation for building a predictive churn model** as a next step.\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  }\n",
